   962                        ;**************************************************************************************************
   963                        ;This is the IRQ handler entry point for the SC28L92 DUART.
   964                        ; This is the first IRQ handler unless an IDE device is found during cold start. By default, it
   965                        ; will take 25 clock cycles to arrive here after an interrupt is generated. If an IDE device is
   966                        ; present, the IDE handler will be processed first. If no IDE interrupt is active, it will take
   967                        ; an additional 33 cycles to arrive here.
   968                        ;
   969                        ; The ISR checks for interrupt sources as follows:
   970                        ; - Timer/Counter, to ensure accurate software RTC and benchmark/delay timings
   971                        ; - Serial Port 2, to provide fast data transfers to a separate device
   972                        ; - Serial Port 1, for standard Console access
   973                        ;
   974                        INTERUPT0                               ;Interrupt 0 to handle the SC28L92 DUART
   975 00:FB00: AD 05 FE                     LDA     UART_ISR        ;Get the UART Interrupt Status Register (4)
   976 00:FB03: F0 1E                        BEQ     REGEXT_0        ;If no bits are set, exit handler (2/3)
   977                        ;
   978 00:FB05: 89 08                        BIT     #%00001000      ;Test for Counter ready (RTC) (2)
   979 00:FB07: D0 1D                        BNE     UART_RTC        ;If yes, go increment RTC variables (2/3)
   980                        ;
   981 00:FB09: 89 40                        BIT     #%01000000      ;Test for Break on B (2)
   982 00:FB0B: D0 D5                        BNE     UARTB_BRK       ;If yes, Reset the DUART receiver (2/3)
   983                        ;
   984 00:FB0D: 89 20                        BIT     #%00100000      ;Test for RHR B having data (2)
   985 00:FB0F: D0 85                        BNE     UARTB_RCV       ;If yes, put the data in the buffer (2/3)
   986                        ;
   987 00:FB11: 89 10                        BIT     #%00010000      ;Test for THR B ready to receive data (2)
   988 00:FB13: D0 A3                        BNE     UARTB_XMT       ;If yes, get data from the buffer (2/3)
   989                        ;
   990 00:FB15: 89 04                        BIT     #%00000100      ;Test for Break on A (2)
   991 00:FB17: D0 5C                        BNE     UARTA_BRK       ;If yes, Reset the DUART receiver (2/3)
   992                        ;
   993 00:FB19: 89 02                        BIT     #%00000010      ;Test for RHR A having data (2)
   994 00:FB1B: D0 0C                        BNE     UARTA_RCV       ;If yes, put the data in the buffer (2/3)
   995                        ;
   996 00:FB1D: 89 01                        BIT     #%00000001      ;Test for THR A ready to receive data (2)
   997 00:FB1F: D0 2A                        BNE     UARTA_XMT       ;If yes, get data from the buffer (2/3)
   998                        ;
   999                        ; if none of the above bits caused the IRQ, the only bit left is the change input port.
  1000                        ; just save it in the temp IRT register in page zero and exit.
  1001                        ;
  1002 00:FB21: 85 E5                        STA     UART_IRT        ;Save the 28L92 ISR for later use (3)
  1003 00:FB23: 6C 0A 02     REGEXT_0        JMP     (IRQRTVEC0)     ;Return to Exit/ROM IRQ handler (6)
  1004                        ;
  1005 00:FB26: 4C 4B FC     UART_RTC        JMP     UART_RTC0       ;Jump to RTC handler (3)
  1006                        ;
  1007                        ;**************************************************************************************************
  1008                        ;ISR Routines for SC28L92 Port A
  1009                        ;
  1010                        ; The Receive Buffer is checked first to ensure there is open space in the buffer.
  1011                        ; By loadng the input count, bit7 will be set if it is full, which will set the "N"
  1012                        ; flag in the CPU status register. If this is the case, we exit to BUFFUL_A and set
  1013                        ; a bit in the SC28L92 Misc. Register. If the buffer has space, we continue.
  1014                        ; 
  1015                        ; To take advantage of the onboard FIFO, we test the RxRDY bit in the Status Register.
  1016                        ; If the bit is set, the FIFO has data and the routine moves data from the FIFO into
  1017                        ; the Receive buffer. We loop back and contnue moving data from the FIFO to the buffer
  1018                        ; until the RxRDY bit is cleared (FIFO empty). If the FIFO is empty, we branch and
  1019                        ; check for a pending Transmit interrupt, just to save some ISR time.
  1020                        ;
  1021                        ; NOTE: the receiver is configured to use the Watchdog function. This will generate a
  1022                        ; receiver interrupt within 64 bit times once data is received (and the FIFO has not
  1023                        ; reached it's configured fill level). This provides the required operation for use
  1024                        ; as a console, as single character commands are common and would not fill the FIFO,
  Sat Apr  4 2026 16:30                                                                                                    Page 24


